<a href="https://codereview.chromium.org/692203002/diff/1/chrome/browser/speech/tts_controller_impl.cc#newcode478" rel="nofollow">https://codereview.chromium.org/692203002/diff/1/chrome/browser/speech/tts_co...</a>
chrome/browser/speech/tts_controller_impl.cc:478: if (current_utterance_ &amp;&amp;
!current_utterance_-&gt;extension_id().empty()) {
On 2014/10/31 22:33:04, David Tseng wrote:
&gt; Why the redundant check for current_utterance?

Fixed.

<a href="https://codereview.chromium.org/692203002/diff/1/chrome/browser/speech/tts_controller_impl.cc#newcode479" rel="nofollow">https://codereview.chromium.org/692203002/diff/1/chrome/browser/speech/tts_co...</a>
chrome/browser/speech/tts_controller_impl.cc:479: #if !defined(OS_ANDROID)
On 2014/10/31 22:33:04, David Tseng wrote:
&gt; Can this happen? (i.e. an utterance with an extension id set on Android).

No. I copied this from other code where we handle Stop, but I think we can get
rid of the ifdef now. Previously this was code that only compiled on a system
with extensions, but now that&#39;s been abstracted so the ifdef isn&#39;t needed.

<a href="https://codereview.chromium.org/692203002/diff/1/chrome/browser/speech/tts_controller_impl.cc#newcode484" rel="nofollow">https://codereview.chromium.org/692203002/diff/1/chrome/browser/speech/tts_co...</a>
chrome/browser/speech/tts_controller_impl.cc:484:
GetPlatformImpl()-&gt;clear_error();
On 2014/10/31 22:33:04, David Tseng wrote:
&gt; What&#39;s the purpose of doing this?

We do this before every call to the platform TTS so that if it calls back with
an error we know it&#39;s from the latest request.

<a href="https://codereview.chromium.org/692203002/diff/1/chrome/browser/speech/tts_controller_impl.cc#newcode485" rel="nofollow">https://codereview.chromium.org/692203002/diff/1/chrome/browser/speech/tts_co...</a>
chrome/browser/speech/tts_controller_impl.cc:485:
GetPlatformImpl()-&gt;StopSpeaking();
On 2014/10/31 22:33:04, David Tseng wrote:
&gt; Is this behavior part of the web speech spec?I&#39;m curious what it says for
other
&gt; browser navigation like refresh or user navigation. Would this code cover
those
&gt; cases?
&gt; 
&gt; What if I wanted to speak a goodbye message during navigation for example?

See crbug.com/418806, there are concerns about a really long message that the
user would have no way to stop, and adware, and things like that.

The thought is that it should behave like any other tab audio; when you close
the tab it&#39;s gone.

If the user really wants something to say goodbye, they should probably install
an extension or app version, or maybe even something like service workers that
can run when a tab isn&#39;t active.</pre>
